<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05177e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05177e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05177e"> 177(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cantilated</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> This mention of the harp suggests that to that instrument narrative poems were chanted or <mark>cantilated</mark>, often at great length. Words then were of prime consequence, and the bard, even upon the battlefield, would recite the achievements of his fathers, as an incitement to his chieftain. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Folk Song] 182</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
